abstract: The speech indicated how Mr. Biden will bring his “working-class Joe” brand to a more diverse Democratic electorate, with black voters playing a dominant role.
snippet: The speech indicated how Mr. Biden will bring his “working-class Joe” brand to a more diverse Democratic electorate, with black voters playing a dominant role.
lead_paragraph: COLUMBIA, S.C. — South Carolina residents gave former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. a front-runner’s welcome Saturday afternoon, when his recently announced presidential campaign made its first stop in the early primary state that will play a critical role in determining the Democratic presidential nominee.

abstract: It was pushed by Madison Avenue and preached by self-help gurus. Then it entered politics.
snippet: It was pushed by Madison Avenue and preached by self-help gurus. Then it entered politics.
lead_paragraph: If the supposedly unlikable Hillary Clinton didn’t break the highest, hardest glass ceiling in 2016, she made enough cracks in it to encourage others to try again: Six women are competing for the Democratic nomination today. But guess what? We don’t seem to like them either.

headline_main: Fair Play Is No Match for Foul

abstract: The former vice president is defending his friendliness toward Republicans in Washington, saying Mr. Trump doesn’t represent them. But others say that view is naïve.
snippet: The former vice president is defending his friendliness toward Republicans in Washington, saying Mr. Trump doesn’t represent them. But others say that view is naïve.
lead_paragraph: DUBUQUE, Iowa — As Joseph R. Biden Jr. made his way across Iowa on his first trip as a 2020 presidential candidate, the former vice president repeatedly returned to one term — aberration — when he referred to the Trump presidency.

abstract: Six of the 23 presidential candidates have appeared in The Times’s weddings pages. Care to guess which ones?
snippet: Six of the 23 presidential candidates have appeared in The Times’s weddings pages. Care to guess which ones?
lead_paragraph: Before their presidential aspirations became national news, six of the 23 declared candidates in the 2020 election were part of a different type of announcement published in The New York Times: their wedding announcement.

abstract: It’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the stories you might have missed.
snippet: It’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the stories you might have missed.
lead_paragraph: From William Barr’s charged hearing to the latest Democratic White House contender, it’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the biggest stories you might have missed (and some links if you’d like to read further).
headline_main: On Politics: The Biggest Stories of the Week

abstract: As a pillar of the ancien régime, Biden is ill-placed to overturn Trump’s revolution.
snippet: As a pillar of the ancien régime, Biden is ill-placed to overturn Trump’s revolution.
lead_paragraph: Is Donald Trump an aberration? If he is, Joe Biden is the perfect Democratic candidate to defeat him next year, the steady hand that can restore decency, steer a middle course between Wall Street and Main Street, and reinvigorate the shaken liberal democratic order.

abstract: And the surprising strength of the rank and file.
snippet: And the surprising strength of the rank and file.
lead_paragraph: Both of our major political parties are undergoing fundamental disruption, but the disruption is coming from different directions. The Republican Party has been disrupted from the bottom. In 2016, the educated Republican elites were happy to embrace conventional Republican themes. It was the Republican base that was fed up and wanted Trump — something completely different.

abstract: Neither man seems ready for harsh political reality.
snippet: Neither man seems ready for harsh political reality.
lead_paragraph: It’s still very early, but Joe Biden has emerged as the clear front-runner for the Democratic nomination. Bernie Sanders is in second place, although he appears to be fairly far behind, and one poll shows him in a statistical tie with Elizabeth Warren. So what should we think about the men currently leading the field?
